Windows 11 Documentation - OS_Wiki

System Name: Windows 11
Kernel: Windows NT (NT 10.0)
Based on: Windows NT family
Created by: Microsoft
Maintained by: Microsoft
Initial release: October 5, 2021
Source model: Closed source (proprietary)
License: Microsoft Commercial Software License
Architecture support: x86_64 (64-bit) only; no official 32-bit edition
Package manager: Microsoft Store; optional Windows Package Manager (Winget)
Desktop Environment: Windows Shell (Fluent Design)
System type: Desktop / Workstation
Target audience: General users, home users, enterprise environments, gamers, and creators.
Not recommended for: Very old hardware, devices without TPM 2.0 / Secure Boot / UEFI, or users who prefer fully open-source systems.
Official site: https://www.microsoft.com/windows
ISO size for download: varies by edition (typically a few GBs)
Minimum requirements:
- CPU: 1 GHz or faster with 2 or more cores on a compatible 64-bit processor
- RAM: 4 GB
- Storage: 64 GB or more
- Firmware: UEFI, Secure Boot capable
- TPM: Version 2.0
- Graphics: DirectX 12 compatible graphics / WDDM 2.x
- Display: >9" with HD Resolution (720p)

Description: Windows 11 is a proprietary operating system developed by Microsoft as the successor to Windows 10. It features a redesigned interface using Fluent Design, a centered taskbar, and improved window management with Snap Layouts and Snap Groups. Windows 11 requires modern hardware, including TPM 2.0, Secure Boot, and UEFI firmware. It includes the Microsoft Store and supports the Windows Subsystem for Linux (WSL). Support for Android apps via the Amazon Appstore and Windows Subsystem for Android is deprecated and will be discontinued in March 2025.
